tre las universidades ms transparentes de Espaa. Cerca de un centenar de sus investigadores estn considerados entre los ms influyentes del mundo segn Stanford Top 2% Scientists Ranking.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "La 14 edicin del QS World University Rankings by Subject proporciona un anlisis comparativo independiente sobre el rendimiento de ms de 16.400 programas universitarios individuales, cursados por estudiantes de ms de 1.500 instituciones en 96 lugares de todo el mundo, 55 disciplinas acadmicas y cinco grandes reas de estudio.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Ms informacin", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-21 11:37:45.027	2024-11-26 19:33:59.026	\N	2	1	es	\N
163	ueodao9xo5m9k3ucc7gbrpbn	They propose capturing quantum transitions with X-rays	An international team led by the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) has developed a new method to capture topological phase transitions using X-ray absorption spectroscopy. The method, proposed in Reports on Progress in Physics , would overcome the energy resolution limitations of previous techniques, opening up new opportunities to study fundamental materials for applications in optoelectronics.	2024-11-12	[{"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "An international team led by the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) has presented a numerical experiment that opens new possibilities for studying topological phase transitions , that is, changes in the quantum properties of a material without altering its atomic structure.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The results, published in the journal Reports on Progress in Physics, show that it is possible to capture these transitions using a novel approach that overcomes the limitations in energy resolution of previous schemes. These advances are significant because they could facilitate new research into fundamental systems for applications in optoelectronics .", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The work involves researchers from ICFO; the MN Mikheev Institute of Metal Physics of the Ural Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences; King's College London; the University of Salamanca and the Max Planck POSTECH/KOREA Research Initiative. ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Topological phases and quantum entanglement ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Solids, liquids and gases exhibit very different behaviours due to the way their atoms are organised: in solids, the atoms are packed in a regular and compact manner; in liquids, they are close together but move randomly; while in gases, the atoms are much further apart and move freely. These characteristics define the classical phases of matter . However, in the quantum world, new phases of matter emerge that do not depend on the spatial distribution of the atoms , but on the way they are quantumly connected. These are called topological phases .", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In topological phases, some properties of particles within a material are linked by quantum entanglement , a phenomenon whereby two particles can affect each other's state, regardless of the distance between them. This entanglement can extend throughout the system, creating complex patterns that define different topological phases. Thus, a phase transition occurs when the way particles are entangled changes, rather than just their position.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Topological states of matter allow the development of exotic materials , such as those that are insulators in their interior but conductive on the surface. Although there has been great progress in the creation of these materials in recent years, many of them, such as topological insulators induced by ultrashort lasers, only exist while the laser pulse is active, which imposes the need to use ultrafast probes to study them.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Until now, angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) has been a key tool for investigating these systems, but it has a problem: as pulses are shortened to capture the ultrafast dynamics of the material, the energy resolution decreases, making detailed analysis difficult.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "New approach", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In order to overcome these limitations, a team led by the Autonomous University of Madrid, in collaboration with researchers from several international institutions, has proposed a new approach complementary to ARPES. ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In a numerical experiment supported by a theoretical model, the group demonstrated that X-ray absorption spectroscopy allows for the direct capture of topological phase transitions without sacrificing energy resolution. This could open up new opportunities to study materials with applications in optoelectronics, the research of which has been, until now, hampered by the compromised relationship between pulse duration and energy resolution.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In the experiment, the researchers simulated the interaction of two ultrashort pulses, separated by a time delay, on a hexagonal boron nitride (hBN) monolayer. One pulse was a linearly polarized X-ray pulse and the other was a circularly polarized infrared pulse. Varying the polarization of the infrared pulse also changed the absorption of the material, allowing the topological phase of the system to be inferred.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "\\"Our ultrafast scheme is very sensitive to topological phase transitions. When the phase changes, a trace is left in the absorption spectrum. This could be key to studying topological phases and identifying topological phase transitions in some materials. The next step is to design an experiment that allows us to test this idea in a real-world setting,\\" the authors conclude.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "_____________________", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Bibliographic reference:", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Juan FP Mosquera, Giovanni Cistaro, Mikhail Malakhov, Emilio Pisanty, Alexandre Dauphin, Luis Plaja, Alexis Chacn, Maciej Lewenstein and Antonio Picon, Topological phase transitions via attosecond x-ray absorption spectroscopy, Rep. on Prog. Phys. DOI: 10.1088/ 1361-6633/ad889f", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "More scientific culture in  UAM Gazette", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-27 18:43:10.778	2024-11-27 18:43:10.778	\N	1	1	en	Representation of the ultrafast X-ray scheme and the system under investigation. / Reports on Progress Physics.
164	ueodao9xo5m9k3ucc7gbrpbn	They propose capturing quantum transitions with X-rays	An international team led by the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) has developed a new method to capture topological phase transitions using X-ray absorption spectroscopy. The method, proposed in Reports on Progress in Physics , would overcome the energy resolution limitations of previous techniques, opening up new opportunities to study fundamental materials for applications in optoelectronics.	2024-11-12	[{"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "An international team led by the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) has presented a numerical experiment that opens new possibilities for studying topological phase transitions , that is, changes in the quantum properties of a material without altering its atomic structure.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The results, published in the journal Reports on Progress in Physics, show that it is possible to capture these transitions using a novel approach that overcomes the limitations in energy resolution of previous schemes. These advances are significant because they could facilitate new research into fundamental systems for applications in optoelectronics .", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The work involves researchers from ICFO; the MN Mikheev Institute of Metal Physics of the Ural Branch of the Russian Academy of Sciences; King's College London; the University of Salamanca and the Max Planck POSTECH/KOREA Research Initiative. ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Topological phases and quantum entanglement ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Solids, liquids and gases exhibit very different behaviours due to the way their atoms are organised: in solids, the atoms are packed in a regular and compact manner; in liquids, they are close together but move randomly; while in gases, the atoms are much further apart and move freely. These characteristics define the classical phases of matter . However, in the quantum world, new phases of matter emerge that do not depend on the spatial distribution of the atoms , but on the way they are quantumly connected. These are called topological phases .", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In topological phases, some properties of particles within a material are linked by quantum entanglement , a phenomenon whereby two particles can affect each other's state, regardless of the distance between them. This entanglement can extend throughout the system, creating complex patterns that define different topological phases. Thus, a phase transition occurs when the way particles are entangled changes, rather than just their position.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Topological states of matter allow the development of exotic materials , such as those that are insulators in their interior but conductive on the surface. Although there has been great progress in the creation of these materials in recent years, many of them, such as topological insulators induced by ultrashort lasers, only exist while the laser pulse is active, which imposes the need to use ultrafast probes to study them.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Until now, angle-resolved photoemission spectroscopy (ARPES) has been a key tool for investigating these systems, but it has a problem: as pulses are shortened to capture the ultrafast dynamics of the material, the energy resolution decreases, making detailed analysis difficult.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "New approach", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In order to overcome these limitations, a team led by the Autonomous University of Madrid, in collaboration with researchers from several international institutions, has proposed a new approach complementary to ARPES. ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In a numerical experiment supported by a theoretical model, the group demonstrated that X-ray absorption spectroscopy allows for the direct capture of topological phase transitions without sacrificing energy resolution. This could open up new opportunities to study materials with applications in optoelectronics, the research of which has been, until now, hampered by the compromised relationship between pulse duration and energy resolution.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In the experiment, the researchers simulated the interaction of two ultrashort pulses, separated by a time delay, on a hexagonal boron nitride (hBN) monolayer. One pulse was a linearly polarized X-ray pulse and the other was a circularly polarized infrared pulse. Varying the polarization of the infrared pulse also changed the absorption of the material, allowing the topological phase of the system to be inferred.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "\\"Our ultrafast scheme is very sensitive to topological phase transitions. When the phase changes, a trace is left in the absorption spectrum. This could be key to studying topological phases and identifying topological phase transitions in some materials. The next step is to design an experiment that allows us to test this idea in a real-world setting,\\" the authors conclude.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "_____________________", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Bibliographic reference:", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Juan FP Mosquera, Giovanni Cistaro, Mikhail Malakhov, Emilio Pisanty, Alexandre Dauphin, Luis Plaja, Alexis Chacn, Maciej Lewenstein and Antonio Picon, Topological phase transitions via attosecond x-ray absorption spectroscopy, Rep. on Prog. Phys. DOI: 10.1088/ 1361-6633/ad889f", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "More scientific culture in  UAM Gazette", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-27 18:43:10.778	2024-11-27 18:43:10.778	2024-11-27 18:43:10.797	1	1	en	Representation of the ultrafast X-ray scheme and the system under investigation. / Reports on Progress Physics.
178	tlkcj41rq11h6pzxeq46i4wd	'OncoTailor', 'Hive', 'SnapEAT' and 'BarberIA', finalists of the 'Pitch Day' of the UAM Emprende Prototype Program	Eight teams participating in the UAM Emprende Prototype Program for students presented their innovative ideas on June 13 at the Auditorium of Pavilion C of the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM). Of these, four made it to the finals that allow them to enter the project incubator.	2024-05-19	[{"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "On June 13, the Auditorium of Pavilion C of the Autonomous University of Madrid hosted the Pitch Day of the UAM Emprende Prototype Program for students, in which OncoTailor, Hive, SnapEAT and BarberIA qualified as finalists and moved on to the project incubator.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "This program, Prototype, aims to identify, define and validate business proposals for projects presented by the community of the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) through a prototype.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "A total of eight teams of entrepreneurs presented their innovative ideas to a panel of investors and entrepreneurs composed of Leticia Raya, accelerator manager at PwC and member of the Advisory Board of the International Startup Congress in Spain; Carlos Benedito, creator of content, brand and design; Patrick Christian Alain Perrodo, general manager of Crea Activitum R&D Co; Juan Martn Sainz de Vicua, chief of staff at Wavveup; Ismael Teijn, CEO of Let's WoW; Carlos Ortiz, founder of Aloha Poke; and Jorge lvarez Cercadillo, head of UAM Emprende.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The participants presented their innovative ideas for four minutes, which the jury scored through questions with the aim of awarding, at the end of the event, four teams with a pass to the project incubator.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The first round was for SuccesStart with its project to help the productivity of ICT and insurance companies, sectors where most sick leave occurs due to mental illness, with outdoor activities and psychological counselling.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The second team to present was PockAd , presenting an app where young people with social and ecological awareness could earn money by watching videos of sustainable brands.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The third team was Junior Empresa, from the UAM, which seeks to help SMEs internationalize through a team made up of university students.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The fourth team, BarberIA, has an app with Artificial Intelligence (AI) where barbershop users can schedule their appointments, as well as try out how a makeover would look on them before doing it.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "After them, SnapEAT was presented , a team working on an application where, through photographs of your food, the nutritional contribution of each food you eat is analyzed. Next, it was the turn of HIVE , a platform powered by an AI trained to help student exchange students in their study process in a foreign country.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In penultimate place was OncoTailor, a tool for personalized medicine and medical decision-making support for oncological treatments. And finally, Psicoffice, a psychological care service within companies.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "After all the groups had presented their work, the jury deliberated to select the four candidates who made it to the final. The organisers thanked all the participants for their fantastic work and dedication.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "More information", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-21 12:12:59.434	2025-01-24 11:20:45.738	2025-01-24 11:20:45.761	2	1	en	\N
72	whhqsqp1rjuqonkfm0b1pddo	A team of UAM students wins the overall final of the 'European Law Moot Court Competition' in Luxembourg 	The litigation team was made up of four students from the Faculty of Law: Alejandro de la Fuente Garca, Francisco Romero Brenlla, Jos Campuzano Prez and Jess Peregrina Legido. This is the first time that a team from a Spanish university has won the overall final of this competition.	2024-04-16	[{"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "A team of four students from the UAM Faculty of Law has been declared the winner of the overall final of the 'European Law Moot Court Competition', held on April 12 in the Grand Chamber of the Court of Justice of the European Union in Luxembourg. ", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "From left to right, Francisco Romero, Lars Bay-Larsen (Vice-President of the CJEU), Alejandro de la Fuente, Jos Campuzano, Jess Peregrina and Javier Dez-Hochleitner.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The UAM litigation team was made up of two students from the Law degree, Alejandro de la Fuente Garca and Francisco Romero Brenlla, and two from the Double Degree in Law and Business Administration, Jos Campuzano Prez and Jess Peregrina Legido. They were supervised by professors Nuria Bermejo and Javier Dez-Hochleitner and had as coach Rosa Cantarero Garca, a former student of the Double Degree in Law and Business Administration and a practising lawyer. Professor Carmen Martnez Capdevila also joined the team to prepare for the grand final.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In the semi-finals, our students beat the team from Maastricht University and, in the final, the team from Roma Tre University. These teams, together with the City University of London, were the winners of their respective regional finals.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Ninety teams in competition", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Ninety teams from the United States and the EU have participated in this edition of the competition, an international competition that, through participation in a mock trial, rewards the best law students in the European Union. Organised annually by the ELMC Society and sponsored by the Court of Justice of the EU, it is considered the most prestigious competition in the field of Union law and one of the most important in the world in its category . Students litigate in English and French, which increases the level of demand and difficulty of the competition.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "This is the first time that a team from a Spanish university has won the final of this competition . In 2018, the UAM team, which included Rosa Cantarero, was the first Spanish team to reach this final, in which it was a semi-finalist, and in 2023 the UAM team was proclaimed runner-up. Our teams have also achieved other achievements such as being runner-up in the regional final in Ljubljana (2019), and the award for the best written claims and responses submitted to the competition (2020). All of them have been supervised by professors Dez-Hochleitner and Bermejo.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The team made up of Alejandro, Francisco, Jos and Jess qualified for the final after winning the regional final in Vienna last February. They reached this regional final after passing the written phase in which more than eighty teams from around the world participated. To be crowned champions of the regional final, they had to overcome five rounds and eliminated teams from prestigious universities. In particular, in the semi-finals they beat the team from the University of Leuven (Belgium) and in the final they beat the team from the University of Turin (Italy).", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Moot courts at UAM", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The UAM Faculty of Law has made a strong commitment to offering its students the opportunity to participate in Moot Courts, national and international competitions consisting of simulations of processes in which a case is resolved before a judicial body of the highest level.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "According to the Faculty itself, \\"participation in these competitions, in addition to providing students with a clear complement to their legal training, allows them to acquire a set of transversal skills and competencies that will be very useful for their future professional life (such as writing documents, legal argumentation, rhetoric, language practice, time management or teamwork, among many others)\\".", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "More information", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Share on:", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-21 11:45:09.628	2024-11-27 18:48:51.152	\N	2	1	en	From left to right, Francisco Romero Brenlla, Alejandro de la Fuente Garca, Jess Peregrina Legido and Jos Campuzano Prez
