145	cmo7skiwqv9v07550cm981ek	A team from the Faculty of Law, champion of the 3rd edition of the 'Moot Court AEDEUR'	\nYocandra Martnez Martnez, Juan Milln de Meer, Luisa Aragn Lpez and Dino Briatore Najmias, with the advice of their coach Professor Carmen Martnez Capdevila, were the winners of this edition of the 'AEDEUR Moot Court', a university competition to promote the study of European Law in Spain.	2024-03-22	[{"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "On March 15, a team of students from the Faculty of Law of the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) was proclaimed champion of the 3rd edition of the ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://www.aedeur.es/", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "AEDEUR Moot Court ", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": ", in the field of European Union (EU) Law. This university competition is based on a simulated trial and is aimed at students of the Degree in Law or Double Degrees with Law from Spanish universities. Its objective is to promote interest in this area of study and this specialty among university students.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The team was made up of ", "type": "text"}, {"bold": true, "text": "Yocandra Martnez Martnez", "type": "text"}, {"text": " (4th year of the ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://www.uam.es/uam/en/noticias/Doble%20Grado%20en%20Derecho%20y%20Ciencia%20Pol%C3%ADtica", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "Double Degree in Law and Political Science", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": " ), J", "type": "text"}, {"bold": true, "text": "uan Milln de Meer", "type": "text"}, {"text": " (4th year of ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://www.uam.es/uam/derecho", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "the Degree in Law", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": " ), Luisa Aragn Lpez and Dino Briatore Najmias (both 3rd year of ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://www.uam.es/uam/derecho", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "the Degree in Law", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": " ). Their coach was Carmen Martnez Capdevila, a professor in the ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://www.uam.es/ss/Satellite/Derecho/es/1234889450599/subhome/Area_de_Derecho_Internacional_Publico.htm", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "Department of Public International Law at the UAM.", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Eighteen teams from law schools at public and private universities throughout Spain participated in this edition. At the end of January, the 12 teams that had submitted the best written submissions were announced and went on to the oral phase of the competition, which consisted of the reproduction of a hearing before the Court of Justice of the EU at the headquarters of the General Council of the Legal Profession and the Supreme Court.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In the first round, the UAM team faced the Universities of Alcal de Henares (where it acted as defendant) and Castilla-La Mancha (where it assumed the role of plaintiff). In the semi-final they beat the University of Deusto and, in the final, held in the plenary hall of the Supreme Court, they beat the University of Zaragoza.", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-18 22:58:25.629	2024-11-26 19:41:46.972	2024-11-26 19:41:46.988	1	1	en	The team formed by Yocandra Martnez Martnez, Juan Milln de Meer, Luisa Aragn Lpez and Dino Briatore Najmias, with their coach Carmen Martnez Capdevila, in the plenary hall of the Supreme Court. / Photo provided by its authors
155	cv5h8aodb87cyfwfdq4h4nbz	A classification system has been developed to measure the educational value of video games	Researchers from the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM) have created a methodology that evaluates the educational potential of video games, assigning them a classification of up to five stars according to their contribution to education. The tool will allow parents, teachers, developers, companies, user associations, etc. to identify which video games have the most positive impact on users' education.	2024-11-14	[{"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Various investigations have begun to show that certain video games transcend their role of entertainment, revealing themselves as valuable educational tools with positive effects on the development and physical, cognitive and emotional education of users. However, there are also video games that are harmful to education, especially in the case of children and adolescents.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "A team of researchers from the Autonomous University of Madrid (UAM), led by Drs. Agustn de la Herrn Gascn and Jos Pablo Garca Meja, has designed a methodology to evaluate the educational value of video games. Published in the journal Comunicar, this research introduces the CEV 5* tool (Educational Rating of Video Games 5*), a system that classifies the educational potential of any video game by stars, similar to the model used in the hotel industry.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "This classification proposes a new way of analysing video games, allowing parents, teachers, companies, developers, user associations and video gamers to understand them from a pedagogical perspective, beyond their entertainment function. In this way, the study could offer clear and well-founded guidelines for families, educators and the video game industry.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "Evaluating the educational potential of video games", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Research underlines the importance of evaluating video games in terms of their educational potential. Using the CEV 5* tool, video games are rated from 0 to 5 stars, according to their contribution to learning and development. This rating provides users, educators and video game designers with a guide to their educational value.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The study is based on a rigorous and complex validation process carried out by qualified experts who systematically analyse both the educational and potentially harmful elements of each video game. The systematic validation process culminates in a well-founded report and a decision in the form of a star rating. The methodology allows for the approach of knowledge of a diverse nature: disciplinary, transversal (competences, values, virtues) and radical (positive and negative) that can positively or negatively influence the user.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "One of the highlights of the CEV 5* tool is its usefulness for teachers and parents, who will be able to identify the most suitable video games for their students and children, respectively. The star rating, as well as detailed reports, offer guidance to parents, video game companies and users on the educational value of each resource, providing clarity and confidence in the previously analyzed video games.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "Benefits and risks: an educational look at the use of video games", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The research also focuses on the potential risks that certain video game content may have for the education of users, particularly at an early age. However, when used as educational tools in a responsible manner and under pedagogical criteria, video games can enhance learning in disciplines such as mathematics, science, arts, and social and personal skills.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "The CEV 5* tool represents a significant advance in the way society can consider video games, promoting their conscious and responsible use in formal and informal education. Furthermore, our research invites the video game industry to include educational criteria in its products as a sign of socially valuable quality, the authors of the study state.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "In summary, the CEV 5* methodology allows the educational value of any video game to be classified, providing clear guidance for all those related to or interested in video games and/or user education. By applying a star system, similar to that of hotels, it facilitates the interpretation of the pedagogical potential of each video game. The system of validation by experts is applicable to other media, such as films and videos, for use in educational and non-educational contexts, the authors conclude.", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "_____________________", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Bibliographic reference:", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "Garca-Meja, J., & De-La-Herrn, A. (2024). The Educational Potential of Video Games: Its Evaluation Through a Rubric. Comunicar, 79, 59-71. ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://doi.org/10.58262/V33279.6", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "https://doi.org/10.58262/V33279.6  ", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "More scientific culture in  ", "type": "text"}, {"url": "https://www.uam.es/uam/noticias-cientificas", "type": "link", "children": [{"bold": true, "text": "UAM Gazette", "type": "text"}]}, {"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}, {"type": "paragraph", "children": [{"text": "", "type": "text"}]}]	2024-11-27 18:36:05.925	2024-11-27 18:36:05.925	\N	1	1	en	The research also focuses on the potential risks that certain video game content may have for the development of consumers, particularly at an early age.
